work.text: Across roles‚Äîwhether organizing hackathons, leading CS events, or coding in labs and internships‚ÄîI stay hands-on and focused on impact. I like to stay busy, solve problems in real time, and make meaningful contributions. Here's some of what I've done.

potpourri.text: In my spare time, I work on projects that don‚Äôt necessarily fit under a specific category. Following are some of those projects.

DE Inbre.desc:
**(Jun - Aug 2023)**
Delaware IDeA Network of Biomedical Research Excellence (INBRE) is a program that supports biomedical research in Delaware. I was a part of the 2023 cohort, where I worked to develop a program to move physical rehabilitation ‚Äì specifically balance training ‚Äì onto an augmented reality platform. This program introduced me to the HCI Lab. Click the link below to see my research!

Teaching Assistant.desc:
**(2022 - 2023)**
I was a Teaching Assistant for CISC108 - Introduction to Computer Science. In this role, I assisted students in learning the fundamentals of programming in Python, including data structures, algorithms, and problem-solving techniques. I also helped develop course materials and provided support during lab sessions.

*PICTURED*: My resume for the students in my cohort.

Lab Assistant.desc:
**(2023)**
I was a Lab Assistant for CISC210 - Intro to Systems Programming. In this role, I assisted students in learning the fundamentals of systems programming in C, including memory management, file I/O, and low-level programming concepts. I also helped develop course materials and provided support during lab sessions.

*PICTURED*: My pre-class computer setup.

HenHacks 2025.desc:
**(Apr 2024 - May 2025)**
I was responsible for the volunteers at UD‚Äôs 3rd annual Hackathon, HenHacks 2025. Under this role, I recruited, trained, and managed over 80+ volunteers for the near 36 hour event.

Towards Anatomy Education with Generativ.desc: This work presents a VR environment with a generative AI virtual assistant to support human anatomy education, allowing the user to communicate verbally with the virtual assistant. I assisted in the development and testing of the program, along with revision to the submitted paper. Won ‚ÄúHonorable Mention‚Äù at the AIxVR 2024 Conference

Enhanced Physical Rehabilitation: Optimi.desc: A program to move physical rehabilitation ‚Äì specifically balance training ‚Äì onto an augmented reality platform. Developed the program, led and managed a pilot test of the program, including analysis of the effectiveness of VR vs AR, and created and presented poster at NERIC 2023.

Virtual Patient Simulation for Nursing S.desc: This project aims to develop a comprehensive training platform for women‚Äôs health and sexual health. The platform will provide nursing students with various scenarios to help them acquire different skills and competencies. Developed in Unity 3D, the program allows communication between a Midwife and nursing students in training via a virtual avatar.

ChatGPT-assisted Medical Examination tra.desc: This project used the Microsoft Hololens 2 to create a quiz environment to probe medical students on anatomical questions related to their field. In the project were two mediums of communication for ChatGPT: a blackboard that supported TTS and STT, and a GPT-embodied virtual avatar.

Embedded Embodied.desc:
This immersive Unity-based application matches participants with virtual mentors using custom avatars and live voice communication. Built with Unity3D, Photon (Multiplayer & Voice), and Google Workspace APIs, the system leverages pre-submitted Google Forms data to pair mentees with mentors using a matching algorithm. Mentors interact via Text-to-Speech (Azure TTS) buttons mapped from their questionnaire responses, while participants use Push-to-Talk (spacebar). Each user is represented by a personalized 3D avatar with animated expressions and lip-sync support via Salsa LipSync. Real-time room management, matchmaking, and communication are handled by Photon servers.

*PICTURED*: My friend, Rana, being [interviewed by UDaily!](https://www.udel.edu/udaily/2025/march/virtual-reality-nurse-training-tool-computer-science-leila-barmaki/)

UD Computing Promotions Undergraduate Of.desc:
**(Oct 2023 - May 2025)**
As a UD CPU, I was responsible for collaborating with other undergraduate students to create an inviting and exciting Computer and Information Science community at UD. Some of the events I have managed include...

CISC Career Fair (pictured), Whiteboard interview preparation, Meet Your Professors!, Personal Project Showcase, Career Readiness, Concentration/Advising Nights, and more!

Berkely Technology Services Command Cent.desc:
(Jun 2024 - Nov 2024)
At BTS, I worked with enterprise schedulers (TIDAL), computer networking, UNIX/LINUX server management, software development, data center management, and LUMEN & Cisco.

Human-Computer Interaction Lab Research.desc:
**(Jun 2023 - present)**
At the HCI Lab, I primarily developed Unity programs in C# and under .NET for various VR related projects. Additionally, I worked with motion-tracking software and facial scanning and rendering within my projects. Outside of development, I assisted in writing and editing research papers in the lab, including my PI‚Äôs NSF Career grant (which she was awarded).

iMessageToSpotify Scraper.desc: The main purpose of this tool is to take spotify songs sent through iMessage, using the library imessage-reader, and add them into a playlist owned by me (or the person who changes the code for themself). However, I also implemented a spreadsheet uploader, supported by a google API, in order to keep track of who sent every song.

DeerParkLine.desc: DeerParkLine was a project I started with my friend, Eli Brignac, in early 2025 to try and get VIP Cards at the local school bar (ability to skip the line). The program uses geolocation and predictive analysis to suggest the current wait time in total and of your position in the 'Deer Park Line'. We didn't get VIP Cards, so I cancelled the domain.

AutoUpdateArtistPlaylist.desc:
Spotify frustratingly does not auto filter artist playlists, so I wrote a script to do that for me. The script will automatically update a playlist with my favorite songs from an artist. This is useful for artists with large discographies, like Pink Floyd.

*PICTURED*: A list of some of my autoupdated artist playlists.

24Hour Manager.desc: In preparation for a 26 hour road trip to Colorado, my fellow music-addicted companion and I insisted on making a playlist for the journey. With ~150 songs each, we knew this playlist would be a mess. So, I took the liberty of creating a program to manage this playlist, including reordering of songs (s.t. Time leads into Great Gig) and balancing the playlist (s.t. we don‚Äôt listen [Thick as a Brick](https://open.spotify.com/track/0eufeeCADKlpxLA7HATWBW?si=c91af13957784e86) right into [2112](https://open.spotify.com/track/2DMDV9kUEO2WjUHg5acHBY?si=aeafc05042ba4e99)

Spotify Album Wheel Spinner.desc: I have a lot of albums saved on Spotify, and I frequently can‚Äôt choose which to listen to. For that, I developed a site that‚Äôll pull from a user‚Äôs Spotify account and create a wheel of saved albums to spin. ***N.B. Because of Spotify API settings, the project is not for public use, for that, I need to reach out to Spotify***

AutoUpdateLoooong.desc:
I have a playlist titled ‚Äòloooooong‚Äô, it‚Äôs songs I like that are usually 12+ mins. This program automatically updates the playlist.

*PICTURED*: *the* [loooooooong](https://open.spotify.com/playlist/1TUrTonIwvMuLtkaSBLmgE?si=39070b7a903d43e1) playlist.

LastFM Management.desc: LastFM is an application that tracks every song you listen to on a platform (for me, it‚Äôs Spotify). I integrated the Last FM API to find and remove my least listened to songs from my playlists.

Scrolling Display.desc:
A pure C built application that responds to input from a keyboard and displays the input on a scrolling display. The program is built to run on a Raspberry Pi, and is used to display messages in my dorm room.

*PICTURED*: The application displaying my intials, GC, without moving.

Mix Maker.desc: Do you ever get frustrated with Spotify‚Äôs Mix creation? If you‚Äôre employed, probably not. I do!!!! For that, I wrote a script that‚Äôll create mixes based on Genres (i.e. Rap) that‚Äôll produce a mix of only songs I KNOW! Now I can listen to my mixes

ColtonCaulfield.com.desc: A website dedicated to the works of my brother, Colton Caulfield. Developed and maintained by me; design and data managed by Colton.

HoloFlash.desc:
Winner of Best Use of AI in Education at 2024 HenHacks 

Our application empowers students by utilizing Googles Gemini AI to swiftly convert audio files, pdfs, and images into flashcards relating to the inputs subject matter. On top of this, users can also review their flashcards in augmented reality using the Microsoft Hololens, hence the name of our project "Holo-Flash". Developed the HoloLens AR application, along with REST development for the site.

WebsiteSetup.desc: Setting up a website can be a hassle, what if you could do it for free in just a few clicks? WebsiteSetup.py is a script I wrote to help me with that. This script deploys a React Page hosted on GitHub Pages, All managed on CLI.

GavinCaulfield.com.desc: This website! Built in Jan 2025 via React framework, GH-Pages, and love <3

Restaurant Menu.desc: A purely frontend React web page built with my group mates for CISC275 - Intro to Software Engineering. The page mocks a restaurant order page, supporting favorites, ratings, cart ‚Äòorders,‚Äô and much more.

ICPC 2023.desc:
**(2023)**
I had the privilege of representing University of Delaware CIS at the International Competitive Programming Competition at John Hopkins. My teammates and I diligently brainstormed for 5+ hours on about 8 difficult programming scenarios, submitting solutions as we went.

Finding Nolan.desc: In 2021-22, I sought out to create a movie with my floormates called *Finding Nolan*. I wrote, edited, filmed, and directed the entire piece. It is a ~35 min epic on *YouTube*. Check it out.

Dance Academic Program Review.desc:
I was invited as one of six students in the School for Dance & Theater at UD attend the bi-decadely Academic Program Review (APR) in 2025. 'The Academic Program Review (APR) provides academic departments with the opportunity to assess the quality of their teaching, research, and service/engagement activities, as appropriate for the department and/or program. Further, the APRs evaluate the effectiveness of their use of resources and determine their progress toward meeting the unit‚Äôs, college‚Äôs, and University of Delaware‚Äôs goals.

I don't have a picture, as they weren't allowed in the meeting. So, 
*PICTURED*: My friends and I playing *Just Dance 2014*.

Brennan School's Artsapalooza Day.desc:
I was invited to assist Delaware's Brennan School's 2025 Artsapalooza Day, a day where students from the school come together to involve themselves in the arts. The Brennan School is a school for children with *Level 3* Autism Spectrum Disorder, and got to work with these children through movement. It was a tremendous event and incredibly gratifying. I am very proud of this participation.

*PICTURED*: A still shot of movement with the children at the Brennan School.

Annamarie Molecule Project.desc:
I participated in a local dance study to translate molecular movement properties into movement arts. The study was conducted by Annamarie Giancarlo, a student at UD, and was a great experience to see how dance can be used to visualize science.

*PICTURED*: Translation of molecular movement over the z-axis.

Peggle Edits.desc: Peggle is awesome. In my free time I made a highlight reel, because I felt like it.

Computationally Random Choreography.desc:
I created an original choreography and a computer-generated one, then presented both to an audience to see if they could distinguish between them. What began as a dance-based Turing Test evolved into a deeper exploration of intention in art and the role of computation in creative expression.
I encourage you to read the paper below.
links: Test your ability to recognize a CRC!

Septronix.desc: Off a whim and a *drummer wanted* poster, I joined Brandon and Steven‚Äôs band *Septronix* in 2023. In the last two years, the three of us have bonded to a great trio, working on live music, playing at gigs, and developing original songs for studio release. As of June 2025, we have release two singles, *No More Chances* and *Sometimes*, with an EP on the way!

Colors of Old College.desc:
Over 5 weeks, a cohort of dancers and I worked with each other to strengthen interpretive movement from art to perform at UD's 'Colors of Old College:  an immersive, multimedia exhibition that unveils the evolving story of Old College, tracing its journey from its 1830s origins to its present-day prominence.' With the assistance of choral singers and an actor, we responded to the words of a journal written by a UD student in 1850! Phenomenal experience.

*PICTURED*: A still frame from the exhibit.

The Diner.desc: A collaborative video created by my group for my final in DANC209 - Dance in Film. The video illustrates the deficit stalking may have on somebody. Selected from the class and presented at the end of the year showcase, *Last Chance to Dance*.

Percussion & Drums.desc: Began playing percussion in 2013, drums in 2016, and haven‚Äôt put either down since.

Piano.desc: My second main instrument. I began playing in 2016, learning from my percussive background of xylophone and mallet instruments. I love the piano, and appreciate integrating it into my work as much as I can.

Other instruments.desc: There are other instruments I am capable of playing, but don‚Äôt consider my main instruments. These include guitar, ukulele, trumpet, and bass (unless you include the recorder too üòâ)

Barstool Delaware.desc: Made it onto Barstool Delaware. Thought it was kinda tuff.

John Rhea Meeting.desc: In 2025, I had the opportunity to shadow a developed Web Designer at Virginia Humanities. John Rhea is an active computer scientist and web designer, and I learned a lot about the field from him. I am very grateful for this opportunity. Cool dude!

human.text: Driven by creativity, curiosity, and neurodivergence, I approach every project with intention and care‚Äîdown to the font choice and color palette. Since childhood, I‚Äôve sought creative outlets, and today I blend that creativity with analytical thinking across my work, hobbies, and personal projects.

programmer.text: I work across many languages‚Äîincluding Python, C/C++, and JS/TSX‚Äîand I treat each project with care, rarely stepping away until it meets my personal standard. I often code in bursts, sometimes as a way to recharge mentally before diving back into one of my creative outlets. PICTURED: Gavin and his friend Eli celebrating their hackathon submission HoloFlash in 2024.

musician.text: From a young age, I‚Äôve been driven by music. I picked up percussion in 4th grade and haven‚Äôt put it down since. Over the years, I‚Äôve added instruments like piano and guitar to the mix. My band, Septronix (pictured left), recently released our latest single, 'Sometimes' ‚Äî check it out!

dancer.text: I‚Äôve been moving my whole life‚Äîwhether in response to dopamine, in a freeform studio space, or just out and about. Dance challenges my brain, grounds me, and connects me to the world around me. Although I‚Äôm relatively new to formal dance education‚Äîhaving taken my first Modern Dance class in Fall 2023‚ÄîI fell in love with the art and now dance whenever I can.

Computationally Random Choreography.desc:
Today, I participated in my Dance Capstone Symposium: a collection of interdisciplinary dance research projects from over 20 dance minors @ UD! I am tremendously proud to share the completion of my research: Computationally Random Choreography. I am tremendously proud of myself and my work as this integrated all important components to my life: computing, dance, and (original!) music. I have included the Abstract to the paper below, along with the project link, with more information. I encourage you to read the paper.


[Final Paper](/file?src=CRC.pdf)


ABSTRACT: Often considered divergent disciplines, computer science and dance share limited intellectual crossover in research and literature. Where work exists, the resources are often unidirectional; dance will support or frame the computer science-driven investigation, and rarely be reversed. Under these constraints, the implications of computer science in a dance (creative) environment are not adequately covered. This study investigates the gap between creative ambiguity and computational determinism. I propose two choreographed performances and a collection of interpreted results from a 10-person pilot study. The first performance features original choreography prepared for film, accompanied by original (non-movement-influential) music. The second performance, known as a Computationally Random Choreography (CRC), was created by a Bash script with FFmpeg software to shuffle the frames of the original performance; code excerpts are available in the Appendix. The randomized sequence was interpreted and performed on film with another original musical accompaniment. A pilot study analyzing the interpretation and perception of both videos revealed insight into computational perception and artistic intent. Surprisingly, the randomized choreography did not hinder emotional resonance‚Äîparticipants often described the CRC as expressive, deliberate, and even more emotionally complex than the original. These findings suggest that randomness, when interpreted through human movement, can generate compelling artistic outcomes and challenge assumptions about authorship, creativity, and meaning in dance. Moreover, the integration of creative ambition into computer science development and education is essential, fostering interdisciplinary innovation and redefining how we perceive both artistic and computational possibility.

HENHACKS!!!.desc:
For the past seven months, I've had the privilege, honor, and absolute pleasure of planning HenHacks 2025, the University of Delaware‚Äôs very own hackathon. From hacking in past years to recruiting, organizing, managing, training, and hiring volunteers, I‚Äôve experienced an indescribable whirlwind of excitement, challenge, and intensity. 

I don‚Äôt believe I can translate the emotions of this experience into words‚Äîlet alone a Highlight post. I don't believe I can convince you of the energy, the camaraderie, or the sheer love that fueled this team. I don't believe that it‚Äôs over. 

But I do believe, and I can say with absolute certainty, that we built something incredible: I believe we made the most unforgettable, innovative, and well-executed CIS hackathon to date.

I‚Äôd revel in my emotions and pour my heart onto this screen to share the overwhelming love this event has left me with‚Äîbut I‚Äôd miss the feeling too much to let it go. So instead, I‚Äôll share the stats that mean the most to me and express my deepest gratitude to those who made HenHacks 2025 possible.

In one weekend, we had
---- ---- ---- ---- ---- ---- ---- 
| $11.5K in prizes awarded to our winners üèÜ 
| Nearly 500 participants! ü´Ç 
| FIFTY-THREE UNIVERSITIES ü§Ø 
| one ripped pants üëñ 

To all the interns, and especially to my very own Volunteering Committee Intern, and my newfound friend, Rebecca Forman, thank you -- you all inspire me to be better.

To my fellow committee heads and new friends, thank you. Your trust, leadership, and unwavering support convinced me to believe‚Äîin this event, in this team, and in myself.

To my admins‚ÄîElla Wilkins, Giovanna Scozzaro, Nazim Karaca, and Debra Yarrington‚Äîyour courage, transparency, and relentless dedication pushed this hackathon to its fullest potential. None of this would have been possible without you.

To my internship at Berkley Technology Services, your commitment and sponsorship elevated HenHacks 2025 to new heights. Your support didn't just fuel this event‚Äîit fueled innovation, collaboration, and an unforgettable experience for all. Thank you.

Finally, thank you HenHacks. ü©∑
